Mexico Stocks: Grupo Mexico Falls; Penoles, Minera Frisco Climb

-- B y   B r y a n   G i b e l
-- 
2011-07-25T21:40:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-22/mexico-stocks-bimbo-cemex-shares-decline-femsa-advances.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  Mexico  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4:30 p.m. New York time.  The IPC index fell 0.8 percent to 35,479.67.  Grupo Mexico SAB (GMEXICOB MM), the country’s largest
mining company, declined 1.3 percent to 42.26 pesos. The company
said July 22 that it has been notified of a lawsuit by Grupo
Aeroportuario del Pacifico SAB, seeking an injunction to block
the mining company’s offer to buy shares of the airport group
known as GAP.  Mines: Gold futures climbed to a record $1,624.30 an ounce
as U.S. lawmakers failed to reach an agreement on raising the
federal debt limit, boosting demand for the metal as a haven
investment. Silver futures for September delivery rose 23.9
cents, or 0.6 percent, to $40.361 an ounce on the Comex.  Industrias Penoles SAB (PE&OLES* MM), Mexico’s largest
silver producer, gained 0.9 percent to 517.87 pesos, its highest
price since it began trading in 1992. Minera Frisco SAB
(MFRISCOA MM), billionaire  Carlos Slim ’s mining company, which
produces silver and gold, rose 2 percent to 56.57 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Bryan Gibel in New York at 
